Let S \triangleright  P be a container. A lmf-container (lax-monoidal-functor-container) [uustalu2017] on S \triangleright  P is given by the following data:

       \begin {align*}            \iota  &: S\\     \otimes  &: S \to  S \to  S\\     \text {pr} &: \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{s' : S\}} P\ (s \otimes  s') \to  P\ s \times  P\ s'        \end {align*}   

  satisfying the equations:

       \begin {align*}            s \otimes  \iota  &= s\\     \text {pr}_1\ p &= p\\     \iota  \otimes  s &= s\\     \text {pr}_2\ p &= p\\     (s \otimes  s') \otimes  s'' &= s \otimes  (s' \otimes  s'')\\     \text {pr}_1\ (\text {pr}_1\ p) &= \text {pr}_1\ p\\     \text {pr}_1\ (\text {pr}_2\ p) &= \text {pr}_2\ (\text {pr}_1\ p)\\     \text {pr}_2\ p &= \text {pr}_2\ (\text {pr}_2\ p)        \end {align*}   

  We abbreviate \pi _1 \circ  \text {pr} as \text {pr}_1 and \pi _2 \circ  \text {pr} as \text {pr}_2. Each set of laws for \text {pr} hold up to the laws for \oplus  above them.

Let (S \triangleright  P, \iota ^S, \otimes ^S, \text {pr}^S) and (T \triangleright  Q, \iota ^T, \otimes ^T, \text {pr}^T) be lmf-containers.
  A distributive law of S \triangleright  P over T \triangleright  Q is given by the data:

       \begin {align*}            &u_1 : \prod _{s : S} (P\ s \to  T) \to  T \\     &u_2 : \prod _{s : S} \prod _{f : P\ s \to  T} Q\ (u_1\ s\ f) \to  S \\     &v_1 : \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to  T\}} \prod _{q : Q\ (u_1\ s\ f)} P\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q) \to  P\ s \\     &v_2 : \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to  T\}} \prod _{q : Q\ (u_1\ s\ f)} \prod _{p : P\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q)} Q\ (f\ (v_1\ q\ p)) \\        \end {align*}   

  where the following equalities hold:

       \begin {align*}            u\ \iota ^S\ (\lambda  \_ . t) &= (t , \lambda  \_ . \iota ^S)\\     u\ s\ (\lambda  \_. \iota ^T) &= (\iota ^T , \lambda  \_. s)\\     v\ \{\iota ^S\}\ \{\lambda  \_. t\} &= \langle  \pi _2 , \pi _1 \rangle \\     v\ \{s\}\ \{\lambda  \_. \iota ^T\} &= \langle  \pi _2 , \pi _1 \rangle \\     \\      u_1\ (s \otimes ^S s')\ (f \circ  \text {pr}^S) &= u_1\ s\ (\lambda  p . u_1\ s'\ (f\ p))\\     u_2\ (s \otimes ^S s')\ (f \circ  \text {pr}^S)\ q &= (u_2\ s\ (\lambda  p . u_1\ s'\ (f\ p))\ q) \otimes ^S (\lambda  p . u_2\ s'\ (f\ (v_1\ q\ p))\ (v_2\ q\ p))\\       \text {pr}^S_1\ (v_1\ q\ p) &= v_1\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p)\\     \text {pr}^S_2\ (v_1\ q\ p) &= v_1\ (v_2\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\\     v_2\ q\ p &= v_2\ (v_2\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\\     \\     u_1\ s\ (\lambda  p . f\ p \otimes ^T g\ p) &= (u_1\ s\ f) \otimes ^T (\lambda  q . u_1\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q)\ (\lambda  p . g\ (v_1\ q\ p)))\\     u_2\ s\ (\lambda  p . f\ p \otimes ^T g\ p)\ q &= u_2\ (u_2\ s\ f\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q))\ (\lambda  p . g\ (v_1\ q\ p))\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\\     v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p) &= v_1\ q\ p\\     v_2\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p) &= \text {pr}^T_1\ (v_2\ q\ p)\\     v_2\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p &= \text {pr}^T_2\ (v_2\ q\ p)        \end {align*}
